            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Chalcol",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The better orthography is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Calcol",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " which A.V. gives for the same name in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In that passage we find (with a slight modification of the last) the four names of this verse all mentioned as sons of Zerah, the son of Judah. These would therefore be greatgrandsons of Jacob. The difference between the name Darda ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "דרדע",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and Dara ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "דרע",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") may be due only to a slip of the transcriber. But no tradition has survived which tells of the special wisdom of this family, nor can we connect the name ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Mahol",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as the father of some of them at least is here called, with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Zerah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But the occurrence of the four names together in one family inclines to the opinion that these men were the men spoken of here. Their fame, even if not at first great, may have grown so during the time between Judah and Solomon.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in all nations",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] We know that it had reached the queen of Sheba. See chap. 10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 31.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Heb. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "he was wiser than all men",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Keil adds \"of his time,\" but we have no right to restrict the words to his contemporaries (see note on chap. 3:12). It is very doubtful whether the names mentioned presently are those of contemporaries] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "than Ethan the Ezrahite, and Heman, and Chalcol, and Darda",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [It is impossible to say whether these are the same persons as the Ethan and Heman and Chalcol and Dara of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or the Ethan and Heman who were David's singers. The resemblance is certainly remarkable. Not only are the names practically the same (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Dara",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may well be a clerical error: many MSS., together with the Syr. and Arab., read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Darda",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but they occur in the same order. Our first impression, consequently, is that the two lists represent the same persons, and if so, these four sages were the \"sons\" of Zerah, the son of Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 38:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But against this it is urged that Ethan is here called the Ezrahite, as are both Ethan and Heman in the titles of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 89",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and 88. respectively. The resemblance, however, of Ezrahite (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "אֶזְרָתִי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to Zerahite (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "זַרְתִי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is so close as to suggest identity rather than difference. There is, perhaps, more weight in the objection that Chalcol and Darda are here distinctly said to be \"the sons of Mahol,\" though here again it has been observed that Mahol (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מָחול",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") means ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "pipe",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "dance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the \"sons of Mahol,\" consequently, may merely be a synonym, agreeably to Eastern idiom (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 12:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", with which cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), for \"musicians.\" We may therefore allow that the four names may be those of sons (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", descendants) of Zerah. But the question now presents itself: Are Ethan and Heman to be identified with the well known precentors of David? Against their identity are these facts: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "1.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That Ethan the singer (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is described as the son of Kishi (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), elsewhere called Kushaiah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 15:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and of the family of Merari; as a Levite that is, instead of a descendant of Judah, and that Heman, who is called the singer, or musician (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the \"king's seer\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 25:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is said to be a son of Joel, a grandson of the prophet Samuel, and one of the Kohathite Levites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 15:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The first impression in this case, therefore, is that they ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "must be",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " distinct. But it should be remembered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that the sons - in the strict sense - of Zerah are nowhere else named for their wisdom, whereas the royal singer and seer probably owed their appointments to their genius, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that though Levites, they may have been incorporated (possibly like Jair, through marriage - see note on ver. 13 above, and cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 2:61",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") into the tribe of Judah. The Levite in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 17:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is spoken of as belonging to the family of Judah, because he dwelt in Bethlehem of Judah, and Elkanah the Levite is called an  Ephraimite in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", because in his civil capacity he was incorporated into the tribe of Ephraim\" (Keil). It must be admitted, however, that the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "natural",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " interpretation of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is that the \"sons\" of Zerah there mentioned were his immediate and actual descendants, and not Levites who long centuries afterwards were somehow incorporated into his family. But the question is one of so much nicety that it is hardly possible to come to a positive conclusion] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and his fame",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Heb. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "name",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "was in all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Heb. all the] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "nations round about",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". [Cf. 10:24, etc.] 1 Kings 4:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "\"He was wiser than all men (of his time), than Ethan the Ezrachite and Heman, Chalcol and Darda, the sons of Machol.\" These four persons are most probably the same as the \"sons of Zerach\" (Ethan, Heman, Calcol, and Dara) mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", since the names perfectly agree, with the exception of דּרע for דּרדּע, where the difference is no doubt attributable to a copyist's error; although, as the name does not occur again, it cannot be decided whether Dara or Darda is the correct form. Heman and Ethan are also called Ezrachites (האזרחי) in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 88:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 89:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and אזרחי is another form of זרחי, the name of the family of Zerach the son of Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 26:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), lengthened by א prosthet. But they were both Levites - Heman a Korahite of the line of Kohath and a grandson of Samuel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:18-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and Ethan a Merarite (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:29-32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 15:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and the president of the Levitical vocal choirs in the time of David (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 15:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and Heman was also \"the king's seer in the words of God\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 25:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Their Levitical descent is not at variance with the epithet Ezrachite. For as the Levite in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 17:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is spoken of as belonging to the family of Judah, because he dwelt in Bethlehem of Judah, and as Samuel's father, Elkanah the Levite, is called an Ephraimite in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", because in his civil capacity he was incorporated into the tribe of Ephraim, so Heman and Ethan are called Ezrachites because they were incorporated into the Judaean family of Zerach. It by no means follows from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that they were lineal descendants of Zerach. The whole character of the genealogical fragment contained in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". shows very clearly that it does not give the lineal posterity of Zerach with genealogical exactness, but that certain persons and households of that family who had gained historical renown are grouped together without any more precise account of their lineal descent. Calcol and Darda (or Dara) are never met with again. It is no doubt to these two that the expression מחול בּני refers, though it cannot be determined whether מחול is a proper name or an appellative noun. In support of the appellative meaning, \"sons of the dance,\" in the sense of sacras choreas ducendi periti, Hiller (in the Onomast. p. 872) appeals to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 12:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"daughters of song.\" - \"And his name was,\" i.e., he was celebrated, \"among all the nations round about\" (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:23-24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]